            <biogHist>
                <p>Peter Bain was born to George Bain, farmer and shoemaker, and Williamina Bain n√©e
                    Campbell. He had at least three surviving siblings in 1841. In 1864, he married
                    Catharine MacLeod, the daughter of a police officer in Lochmaddy, North Uist and
                    by this time Peter had become a Preventiveman, working for the Inland Revenue.
                    The following year the couple had a son William and then twin boys George
                    Alexander and Peter in 1867, although both twins only lived a few days. In 1869,
                    another son was born, also called George Alexander, but following the birth
                    Catharine died of a postpartum haemorrhage. By 1871, Peter Bain is recorded as a
                    lodger in Kyleakin and in 1881 he is in Stornoway with sons William and George.
                    By 1891, Peter Bain had married again, Barbara MacLeod, in Lochbroom, Ullapool
                    and they appear to have had at least one child together. </p>
                <p>Peter Bain died of an abdominal tumour in 1891 in Lochbroom, Ullapool and his son
                    George Alexander Bain signed the death certificate.</p>
                <p>In 1866 Peter met with Alexander Carmichael and copied two manuscripts for him.
                    Carmichael had been lent the manuscripts by Mr Donald MacDonald, Kallin,
                    Grimsay, North Uist, son of the late Lieutenant James MacDonald who wrote the
                    manuscripts.</p>
